00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:41.780
- One of the things people
predict is the Higgs boson.

00:07:41.780 --> 00:07:44.690
The idea is that Higgs
boson is the particle that

00:07:44.690 --> 00:07:47.145
is responsible for giving
mass to the other particles.

00:07:47.145 --> 00:07:48.770
So anything that is
going to have mass,

00:07:48.770 --> 00:07:50.270
it means it has stuff to it.

00:07:50.270 --> 00:07:52.010
It's not actually stuff.

00:07:52.010 --> 00:07:53.840
Earlier I was saying
the electron has mass,

00:07:53.840 --> 00:07:54.900
but it has no volume.

00:07:54.900 --> 00:07:55.750
How can that be?

00:07:55.750 --> 00:07:58.160
It turns out mass
is probably just

00:07:58.160 --> 00:08:01.019
characteristic of a particle,
the way like charge is.

00:08:01.019 --> 00:08:03.060
Like, some particles have
charge, like electrons.

00:08:03.060 --> 00:08:03.939
Some particles don't.

00:08:03.939 --> 00:08:05.480
It's just a different
kind of charge.

00:08:05.480 --> 00:08:09.070
So you can think of mass as
sort of gravitational charge.

00:08:09.070 --> 00:08:12.530
And when two things both have
mass, they attract each other.

00:08:12.530 --> 00:08:14.750
Interestingly, you
can't have negative mass

00:08:14.750 --> 00:08:17.585
or repulsive gravity.

00:08:17.585 --> 00:08:18.085
All right.

00:08:18.085 --> 00:08:19.610
So the collision happens.

00:08:19.610 --> 00:08:22.430
It lasts for like 10 to
the negative 23 seconds.

00:08:22.430 --> 00:08:24.530
And you get one measurement.

00:08:24.530 --> 00:08:27.410
So if you say, well,
I'm going to plot

00:08:27.410 --> 00:08:29.127
the mass, the total
energy, of this guy.

00:08:29.127 --> 00:08:30.710
I'm going to add
this guy and this guy

00:08:30.710 --> 00:08:33.140
together and add
the total energy,

00:08:33.140 --> 00:08:36.350
this axis here is
number of collisions.

00:08:36.350 --> 00:08:38.875
In your individual experiment,
you get one measurement,

00:08:38.875 --> 00:08:39.559
right here.

00:08:39.559 --> 00:08:41.674
Do another one, you get
another measurement.

00:08:41.674 --> 00:08:42.919
You do another one.

00:08:42.919 --> 00:08:44.740
Eventually, you
build up your data.

00:08:44.740 --> 00:08:48.190
And the data looks
like this, for example.

00:08:48.190 --> 00:08:50.690
And then you have two theories
that predict the data.

00:08:50.690 --> 00:08:53.190
One says, well, I'm going to
predict there's no Higgs boson.

00:08:53.190 --> 00:08:54.470
So the data should
fall along this line.

00:08:54.470 --> 00:08:55.610
And the other is
I'm going to predict

00:08:55.610 --> 00:08:57.010
that plus a Higgs boson.

00:08:57.010 --> 00:08:59.150
And the problem is the
difference between these two

00:08:59.150 --> 00:09:00.610
theories is very small.

00:09:00.610 --> 00:09:02.750
And so it's very
hard to distinguish

00:09:02.750 --> 00:09:07.118
these two with our data because
the predicted effect is tiny.

00:09:07.118 --> 00:09:09.017
If the predicted
effect were huge,

00:09:09.017 --> 00:09:10.850
it would be very easy
to tell the difference

00:09:10.850 --> 00:09:14.200
between with Higgs boson
or not with Higgs boson.

00:09:14.200 --> 00:09:15.899
But the predicted
effect is tiny,

00:09:15.899 --> 00:09:17.190
and so it's really hard to see.

00:09:17.190 --> 00:09:19.510
What you need is a
huge amount of data.

00:09:19.510 --> 00:09:22.180
You need to take a bajilliion
collisions before you

00:09:22.180 --> 00:09:23.310
can see the difference.

00:09:23.310 --> 00:09:26.120
That's why we run this thing
40 million times a second,

00:09:26.120 --> 00:09:29.030
all day, all year, to
get a lot of collisions,

00:09:29.030 --> 00:09:31.065
to tell small differences
between theories.

00:09:31.065 --> 00:09:32.940
It's like when you take
a picture of the sky.

00:09:32.940 --> 00:09:35.480
If you just take a picture,
you get a little bit of light.

00:09:35.480 --> 00:09:38.630
But the longer you leave the
telescope looking at the sky,

00:09:38.630 --> 00:09:40.460
the more you can see
farther away things.

