01:09:30.220 --> 01:09:32.000
The question is like,
could there ever

01:09:32.000 --> 01:09:33.890
be a theory of
everything or could we

01:09:33.890 --> 01:09:35.670
ever understand the universe?

01:09:35.670 --> 01:09:39.939
So I hope not because I
like asking questions.

01:09:39.939 --> 01:09:44.479
But there are some
arguments that the universe

01:09:44.479 --> 01:09:46.444
might have a smallest particle.

01:09:46.444 --> 01:09:49.080
So one way to interpret
your question might be,

01:09:49.080 --> 01:09:51.855
could we ever drill down and
discover the smallest particle

01:09:51.855 --> 01:09:53.979
or is it just going to keep
going forever, smaller,

01:09:53.979 --> 01:09:55.580
and smaller, and
smaller particles?

01:09:55.580 --> 01:09:56.810
Well, we don't know.

01:09:56.810 --> 01:09:59.030
But there are some
arguments that suggest

01:09:59.030 --> 01:10:01.882
that the universe has a small--

01:10:01.882 --> 01:10:04.640
a distance scale beyond
which you can't measure.

01:10:04.640 --> 01:10:07.290
The universe is pixelated
at some smallest level.

01:10:07.290 --> 01:10:09.770
But there is an end to this.

01:10:09.770 --> 01:10:11.360
The arguments are pretty weak.

01:10:11.360 --> 01:10:12.500
They go like this.

01:10:12.500 --> 01:10:14.330
If I take all these
numbers that I

01:10:14.330 --> 01:10:16.370
found about the universe,
the speed of light,

01:10:16.370 --> 01:10:19.327
Planck's constant, Newton's
gravitational constant,

01:10:19.327 --> 01:10:21.410
and I multiply them together
in this creative way,

01:10:21.410 --> 01:10:23.195
I get a number that
has units of distance.

01:10:25.700 --> 01:10:27.477
That's called the Planck length.

01:10:27.477 --> 01:10:28.310
What is that number?

01:10:28.310 --> 01:10:32.450
Well, it's 10 to the minus 35
meters, really, really small.

01:10:32.450 --> 01:10:34.490
Does that mean the
universe is pixelated?

01:10:34.490 --> 01:10:35.190
No.

01:10:35.190 --> 01:10:36.940
Does it mean if the
universe is pixelated,

01:10:36.940 --> 01:10:38.400
it's pixilated at that size?

01:10:38.400 --> 01:10:39.350
No.

01:10:39.350 --> 01:10:41.280
But what do we do in science
when we don't know what to do?

01:10:41.280 --> 01:10:42.390
We do the dumbest thing first.

01:10:42.390 --> 01:10:43.760
So that was the dumbest thing.

01:10:43.760 --> 01:10:45.260
So it's sort of a
hand-wavy argument

01:10:45.260 --> 01:10:48.110
that maybe at that scale,
or somewhere within a factor

01:10:48.110 --> 01:10:49.940
of a million of that
scale, the universe

